Only changing opengl es context from 2.0 to 3.0 significantly improves performance of some of our shaders, without needing any changes in app or cocos2dx code. 

For example, on iPhone6, simply changing context to opengl es 3.0 gives shaders access to 15 varying vectors instead of 8 available when using opengl es 2.0 context (Max Varying Vectors).

On iOS, code change is also very simple, including the fallback to opengl es 2.0 for devices which don't support 3.0. Change this:

cocos/platform/ios/CCES2Renderer-ios.m
```
        if( ! sharegroup )
            context_ = [[EAGLContext alloc] initWithAPI:kEAGLRenderingAPIOpenGLES2];
        else
            context_ = [[EAGLContext alloc] initWithAPI:kEAGLRenderingAPIOpenGLES2 sharegroup:sharegroup];
```
To:
```
        if ( ! sharegroup ) {
            context_ = [[EAGLContext alloc] initWithAPI:kEAGLRenderingAPIOpenGLES3];
            if (context_ == nil) {
                context_ = [[EAGLContext alloc] initWithAPI:kEAGLRenderingAPIOpenGLES2];
            }
        }
        else {
            context_ = [[EAGLContext alloc] initWithAPI:kEAGLRenderingAPIOpenGLES3 sharegroup:sharegroup];
            if (context_ == nil) {
                context_ = [[EAGLContext alloc] initWithAPI:kEAGLRenderingAPIOpenGLES2 sharegroup:sharegroup];
            }
        }
```



On Android also, code change to start using opengl es 3.0 is simply changing this:
cocos/platform/android/java/src/org/cocos2dx/lib/Cocos2dxGLSurfaceView.java
`            this.setEGLContextClientVersion(2);
`
To:
`            this.setEGLContextClientVersion(3);
`

But this (obviously) causes app to crash on devices which don't support 3.0. And I couldn't figure out how to change Cocos2dxGLSurfaceView to fallback to opengl es 2.0 in this case. Android documentation provides some hints for detecting 3.0 support but not for apps using GLSurfaceView, only for apps managing their own EGL context. I hope someone can help with this.
From https://developer.android.com/guide/topics/graphics/opengl.html#version-check
```
private static double glVersion = 3.0;

private static class ContextFactory implements GLSurfaceView.EGLContextFactory {

  private static int EGL_CONTEXT_CLIENT_VERSION = 0x3098;

  public EGLContext createContext(
          EGL10 egl, EGLDisplay display, EGLConfig eglConfig) {

      Log.w(TAG, "creating OpenGL ES " + glVersion + " context");
      int[] attrib_list = {EGL_CONTEXT_CLIENT_VERSION, (int) glVersion,
              EGL10.EGL_NONE };
      // attempt to create a OpenGL ES 3.0 context
      EGLContext context = egl.eglCreateContext(
              display, eglConfig, EGL10.EGL_NO_CONTEXT, attrib_list);
      return context; // returns null if 3.0 is not supported;
  }
}
```

But overall this seems to be a very safe change which will give immediate performance boost to many apps without any code changes, and let them start using new 3.0 features if they want to.

You can check Apple's opengl es 3.0 compatibility checklist to make sure it won't effect cocos2dx engine, but I haven't seen anything failing until now:
https://developer.apple.com/library/content/documentation/3DDrawing/Conceptual/OpenGLES_ProgrammingGuide/AdoptingOpenGLES3/AdoptingOpenGLES3.html

90% iOS devices (iPhone5s and newer) and more than 60% Android devices already support opengl es 3.0 (https://developer.android.com/about/dashboards/index.html#OpenGL).

